🛠 Advanced DevOps Linux Cheat Sheet (50 Essential Commands)
1. System & Service Monitoring

journalctl: Queries and displays logs from systemd.

systemctl: Manages systemd services (start, stop, enable, status).

top / htop: Real-time process monitoring.

dmesg: Displays kernel-level messages and boot logs.

uptime: Shows system load and time since last reboot.

vmstat: Reports virtual memory, CPU, and paging activity.

iostat: Monitors system input/output device loading.

sar: Collects, reports, and saves system activity information.

strace: Traces system calls and signals for debugging applications.

lsof: Lists open files and identifies processes using them.

2. Networking & Diagnostics
ss: Investigates sockets and network statistics.

netstat: Traditional tool for network statistics (legacy, but still used).

dig / nslookup: DNS lookup utilities for troubleshooting.

curl / wget: Transfers data to or from a server (essential for API debugging).

tcpdump: Captures and inspects live network traffic.

nmap: Network scanning and security auditing.

mtr: Combines traceroute and ping for network path diagnostics.

iptables / nftables: Manages firewall and packet filtering rules.

ip addr / ip route: Modern tools for managing interfaces and routing.

ifconfig: Displays or configures network interface parameters.

3. File Operations & System Drift
find: Searches for files in a directory hierarchy based on criteria like time.

rsync: Syncs files and directories incrementally and precisely.

grep / egrep: Searches text using patterns or regular expressions.

sed: Stream editor for filtering and transforming text.

awk: Advanced text processing and reporting language.

xargs: Builds and executes commands from standard input.

du: Estimates file space usage.

df: Reports file system disk space usage.

tar: Archives and compresses files.

chmod / chown: Modifies file permissions and ownership (critical for security).

4. Process & Security Management
ps aux: Displays detailed information about all running processes.

kill: Sends signals to terminate processes.

nice / renice: Adjusts the priority of running processes.

pkill / pgrep: Searches for or signals processes by name.

usermod: Modifies user account settings.

groupmod: Modifies group definitions.

visudo: Safely edits the /etc/sudoers file.

id: Displays user and group identity information.

sshd: Manages the Secure Shell daemon.

umask: Sets the default permissions for new files.

5. Advanced System Administration

screen / tmux: Terminal multiplexers for persistent sessions.

crontab: Schedules recurring jobs.

fdisk / parted: Manages disk partitions.

mount / umount: Manages file system mounting.

chroot: Changes the apparent root directory for a process.

lsblk: Lists all block devices.

udevadm: Device management and debugging.

ldd: Displays shared library dependencies.

logrotate: Manages automated rotation and compression of log files.

free: Displays total, used, and free system memory.






